9:Tbf3,<p>Every high-performing team I've been part of had one thing in common: you could say the uncomfortable thing.</p>
<p>Not because everyone was fearless. Because the trust infrastructure was built well enough that the cost of honesty was low and the cost of silence was high.</p>
<h2>The equation</h2>
<p>I think about trust as:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Trust = Competence × Intent</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Competence means: do you know what you're doing, and do you do what you say?</p>
<p>Intent means: do I believe you want good outcomes for me and for this? Are you honest even when it's inconvenient?</p>
<p>Both legs of the equation matter. A highly competent person with bad intent is dangerous. A well-meaning person with no competence is just exhausting. You need both.</p>
<h2>Reliability is underrated</h2>
<p>In Silicon Valley, everyone talks about capability. Can you code? Can you raise? Can you sell?</p>
<p>Nobody talks about reliability. Which is strange, because reliability is what actually drives trust compound interest.</p>
<p>Showing up when you said you would. Following through on small things when nobody's watching. Being consistent across contexts — the same person with your boss as with your team.</p>
<p>Reliability is the unsexy moat. It's hard to see on a resume. It shows up everywhere in real collaboration.</p>
<h2>Breaking it</h2>
<p>Trust is asymmetric. It takes a long time to build and a short time to destroy.</p>
<p>This isn't a design flaw — it's a feature. High-trust relationships are worth protecting. The asymmetry makes people think twice before acting in bad faith.</p>
<p>What breaks trust:</p>
<ul>
<li>Saying one thing and doing another, even once</li>
<li>Letting people find out things they should have heard from you</li>
<li>Prioritizing comfort over honesty in important moments</li>
<li>Tolerating behavior that violates the group's values</li>
</ul>
<p>That last one is underappreciated. Every time a leader tolerates bad behavior from a high performer, they signal that the rules are conditional. That signal spreads.</p>
<h2>Rebuilding it</h2>
<p>Trust can be repaired. But it requires a path to redemption — visible, sustained change. Not just words.</p>
<p>People are flawed. Relationships depend on forgiveness. But forgiveness doesn't mean ignoring the pattern. It means: I believe you're trying, and I'm watching for evidence.</p>
<p>The organizations that survive long-term have figured out how to hold this tension — high accountability without becoming vindictive, forgiveness without losing standards.</p>
<h2>Building trust infrastructure</h2>
<p>If you're building a team, trust isn't just about relationships. It's about systems.</p>
<p>How do decisions get made transparently? How does feedback flow? What are the explicit values, and how do they get enforced? Who has permission to say the hard thing?</p>
<p>These are design choices. And like all design choices, not making them is also a choice.</p>
<p>Build the infrastructure first. The relationships follow.</p>
